two rockets struck central kabul 
sunday one exploding near the police headquarters and hospital 
officials reported the missiles killed at least 13 people and 
wounded 24 
the officials said most of the victims were standing in line at 
a gasoline station waiting to receive their daily fuel ration 
witnesses said sunday was police day honoring the police force 
and one rocket blew up in a downtown park near police headquarters 
the hospital officials did not know if any policemen were among the 
casualties and the government made no comment on the attacks 
the second rocket exploded near the ministry of mines and 
industry building in the large presidential compound 
many merchants on chicken street the main shopping street lined 
with carpet and antique stores drew the shutters and closed their 
businesses as ambulance crews removed the dead and wounded 
kabul has been the target of almost daily rocket attacks since 
late june with anticommunist guerrillas stationed in the 
surrounding hills firing the missiles into the city the attacks 
have killed more than 350 people and injured about 800 
the marxist government claims the rebels fire the rockets at 
random into kabul to spread panic among civilians and make them 
flee to guerrillacontrolled areas 
the rebels who have been battling government forces for a 
decade have denied some of the rocket attacks and say the kabul 
government fires at its own people 
most of the rebel factions have bases across the border in 
pakistan and receive military aid from the united states while the 
soviet union backs the government 
