<TEXT>
just 37 percent of us executives surveyed 
recently said they have begun implementing strategies to deal with 
the unified european market planned for 1992 
the fact that the majority have not taken action shows they 
may be greatly underestimating the impact of the single european 
market on their businesses said john j hurley director of the 
international division at peat marwickboston 
the 12 membernations of the european economic community plan to 
dissolve market borders at the end of 1992 creating a unified 
market with common product standards and expectations of greater 
competition 
the survey by the accounting firm kpmg peat marwick released 
last week found that most us executives believe a unified europe 
will benefit european firms and that american companies should ally 
with european firms 
peat marwick surveyed executives in four fields considered the 
most likely yo be involved in trade with the ec manufacturing 
high technology merchandising and transportation 
of 10000 surveys mailed in february and march to a random 
sampling of executives 993 were returned and 872 were usable 
according to peat marwick the survey has a sampling error of plus 
or minus 3 percent 
more than half of the executives said they expected the overall 
impact of the common european market on their industries in the 
united states to be minimal 
but 85 percent of the respondents said the merger would benefit 
european firms and 60 percent felt their own industries in europe 
could gain from the unified market 
most executives reported they believe the merger holds pitfalls 
for us companies that are not prepared 
eight in 10 respondents said they felt us companies will be 
pressured to acquire a european identity to gain from the new 
arrangement seventyfive percent of respondents predicted european 
authorities will grant special cost advantages to european 
companies 
one manufacturer counseled his peers against thinking the 
europeans would make it easy for us businesses to compete 
according to the survey 
theyll have the power in their hands theyll have the bat 
the ball and the playing field said the executive who was not 
identified 
eightyseven percent of respondents advised us firms to forge 
alliances with their european counterparts and 81 percent suggested 
the need for americans to increase onsite manufactuing in europe 
the survey reported that large multinational firms in high 
technology and manufacturing are taking the greatest care to 
position themselves well for the new european market 
</TEXT>
